<div class="header">
  <div class="header-content">
    <div class="tag">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</div>
    <h1>Sherwin-Williams (SHW)<br/>Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A transparent, two-stage discounted cash flow valuation of The Sherwin-Williams Company using actual financials, disclosed assumptions, and one final number.</p>
    <p class="date">Updated March 2026</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV !== null ? roundedIV.toFixed(2) : 'N/A'}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${stockData.price !== null ? stockData.price.toFixed(2) : 'N/A'} {marginOfSafety !== null ? `(${marginOfSafety}%)` : ''}</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">{revenueM !== null ? `$${(revenueM / 1000).toFixed(2)}B` : 'N/A'}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">TTM Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">{fcfBase !== null ? `$${(fcfBase / 1000).toFixed(2)}B` : 'N/A'}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Free Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">{stockData.eps !== null ? `$${stockData.eps.toFixed(2)}` : 'N/A'}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">{stockData.operatingMargin !== null ? `${(stockData.operatingMargin * 100).toFixed(1)}%` : 'N/A'}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Operating Margin</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">{netCashM !== null ? `$${(netCashM / 1000).toFixed(2)}B` : 'N/A'}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Cash</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. No multiples, no comparables, no vibes. Just future cash flows discounted to today.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Sherwin-Williams generated <strong>${fcfBase !== null ? `$${(fcfBase / 1000).toFixed(2)} billion` : 'N/A'}</strong> in free cash flow recently. This is operating cash flow minus capital expenditures. This is real cash the business produces after paying for everything, including capital requirements.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow FCF at <strong>{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}% per year</strong> for 5 years. SHW is a mature, steady compounder with a highly defensible moat and strong pricing power in the paints and coatings industry.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}% forever</strong> — roughly GDP growth plus modest pricing power. We use the <strong>Gordon Growth Model</strong>: Terminal Value = FCF₆ ÷ (discount rate − terminal growth rate).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}%</strong> — our required rate of return. This is the cost of equity, considering a 10Y Treasury yield of {treasuryRate} and SHW's market beta.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash ({netCashM !== null ? `$${(netCashM / 1000).toFixed(2)}B` : 'N/A'}) = Equity Value. Divide by shares outstanding ({sharesOutM !== null ? `${sharesOutM.toFixed(2)}M` : 'N/A'}) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Sherwin-Williams is an established dividend aristocrat with pricing power. While revenue growth may be single-digit, strong operating margins, share buybacks, and efficient capital allocation allow Free Cash Flow to compound at a healthy mid-to-high single-digit clip.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        10Y Treasury: {treasuryRate}. Beta: {stockData.beta !== null ? stockData.beta.toFixed(2) : '1.24'}. Using the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM) gives a rate around 11%. We round to a firm 10% hurdle rate — typical for institutional investors assessing large-cap stable companies.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Long-term nominal GDP growth is ~3%. SHW holds dominant market share in the architectural paint segment and faces little disruption risk from new technologies. A 3% terminal growth rate reflects a mature company growing slightly ahead of or in line with inflation forever.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Projected Free Cash Flows</h2>
  {fcfBase !== null ? (
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>FCF ($M)</th>
          <th>PV Factor</th>
          <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Base (Recent TTM)</td>
          <td>${Math.round(fcfBase).toLocaleString()}</td>
          <td>—</td>
          <td>—</td>
        </tr>
        {projectedFCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
            <td>Year {p.year}</td>
            <td>${p.fcf.toLocaleString()}</td>
            <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(4)}</td>
            <td>${p.pvFCF.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td colspan="3">Sum of Phase 1 PV</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  ) : (<p>Unable to fetch FCF projection data.</p>)}

  <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE ═══ -->
  <h3>Terminal Value</h3>
  {terminalValue !== null ? (
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
          <th>Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Year 6 FCF (Year 5 × {(1 + growthRateTerminal).toFixed(3)})</td>
          <td>${Math.round(projectedFCF[4].fcf * (1 + growthRateTerminal)).toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Terminal Value (FCF₆ ÷ ({(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}% − {(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}%))</td>
          <td>${terminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  ) : (<p>Unable to compute Terminal Value.</p>)}

  <!-- ═══ FINAL CALCULATION ═══ -->
  <h3>Final Valuation</h3>
  {equityValue !== null ? (
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
          <th>Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>PV of Phase 1 Cash Flows</td>
          <td>${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
          <td>${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>= Enterprise Value</td>
          <td>${enterpriseValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>+ Net Cash (Cash − Debt)</td>
          <td>${Math.round(netCashM).toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>= Equity Value</td>
          <td>${Math.round(equityValue).toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>÷ Shares Outstanding</td>
          <td>{sharesOutM.toFixed(2)}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>Intrinsic Value Per Share</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  ) : (<p>Unable to perform final calculation.</p>)}

  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Our base case uses {(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}% growth and {(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}% discount rate. But reasonable people disagree on these numbers. Here's what the intrinsic value looks like under different assumptions. Find the combination you believe in.</p>

  {sensitivityTable.length > 0 ? (
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(0)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  ) : (<p>Unable to calculate sensitivity matrix.</p>)}

  <!-- ═══ RISKS ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks & Limitations</h2>
  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pricing power:</strong> SHW has demonstrated immense ability to pass on raw material costs to consumers. If pricing power outpaces volume declines, margins could expand further.</li>
    <li><strong>Share repurchases:</strong> Aggressive share buybacks will reduce the share count, increasing per-share intrinsic value over time.</li>
    <li><strong>Housing boom:</strong> A resurgence in existing home sales or new construction (due to rate cuts) would drastically increase paint volume demand.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Housing market stagnation:</strong> High mortgage rates keeping existing homeowners locked in ("golden handcuffs") reduces turnover, which directly impacts interior/exterior painting demand.</li>
    <li><strong>Raw material costs:</strong> A sudden spike in oil prices or titanium dioxide could compress margins temporarily before price hikes are enacted.</li>
    <li><strong>High Debt Load:</strong> Debt levels remain somewhat elevated from historical acquisitions (like Valspar), leading to significant interest expense.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E multiple?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Multiples tell you what the market <em>is</em> paying — not what a company is <em>worth</em>. A DCF forces you to state explicit assumptions about growth and risk, then lets math determine the price. It's the only valuation method that directly connects cash flow generation to value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is SHW a dividend stock?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Yes, Sherwin-Williams is a well-known dividend grower. However, its starting yield is typically low (often under 1.5%). The total return story is driven by earnings growth, share buybacks, and dividend growth, rather than starting yield.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, and conviction in the assumptions. Always conduct your own research.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

